               <desc type="building-data" xml:lang="en">
                  <p source="#bibl000064b-1" xml:lang="en">The foundation of the original Dajue liushi Hall 大覺六師殿 (destroyed） is located north of the Tianwang Hall, and it originally supported the second timber-frame structure on the central axis. First built during the Northern Song dynasty Yuanfeng reign period (1078-1085 CE), it was heavily damaged during the early 20th century and was unrepairable when Liang Sicheng visited in 1933.</p>
                  <p source="#bibl000064b-1" xml:lang="en">Based on the archeological evidence, it is nine bays wide and six bays deep and was the largest building in the complex, measuring 53 meters wide and 35 meters deep and it originally had a single-eave xieshan roof. The name of the building suggests its dedication to the six Buddhas that predated the historical Buddha, Shakyamuni.</p>
               </desc>
